 the patch. The fraction of the captured N from the organic patch as a percentage of the plants' total N, however, did differ among species. Substantial amounts ({\textgreater}62\%) of the 15N initially added remained in the patch at harvest. Much less (c. 13–21\%) 13C remained in the patch. Protozoan biomass and nematode numbers increased significantly (P{\textless}0·05) in the organic patch, although the relationship between the two groups was not significant. As in the inorganic N study, the relationship between log protozoan biomass and NO3− concentrations in the soil was significantly positive. We conclude that, when grown in monoculture, plants' N capture from an organic patch is not a simple function of root proliferation. External factors, not plant attributes, are more important in controlling patch exploitation.},
